sion and reformulation. Far from being a vague term, as postwar historiography has so often claimed, for Japanese of all backgrounds who came of age from the 1920s to the 1940s, fascism conjured up a set of concrete associations, including nationalism, leadership, economics, and a drive toward empire and a new world order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFascismzItalyxHistory. 0aFascismzJapanxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezItaly. 0aPolitical culturezJapan. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aFascism, Japan, Transnational, ultra-nationalism, Mussolini.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145636740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456367423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801456367/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles